fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Categories for the Working Mathematician provides an array of general ideas useful in a wide variety of fields. Starting from the foundations, this book illuminates the concepts of category, functor, natural transformation, and duality. The book then turns to adjoint functors, which provide a description of universal constructions, an analysis of the representations of functors by sets of morphisms, and a means of manipulating direct and inverse limits. These categorical concepts are extensively illustrated in the remaining chapters, which include many applications of the basic existence theorem for adjoint functors. The categories of algebraic systems are constructed from certain adjoint-like data and characterized by Beck's theorem. After considering a variety of applications, the book continues with the construction and exploitation of Kan extensions. This second edition includes a number of revisions and additions, including two new chapters on topics of active interest. One is onsymmetric monoidal categories and braided monoidal categories and the coherence theorems for them. The second describes 2-categories and the higher dimensional categories which have recently come into prominence. The bibliography has also been expanded to cover some of the many other recent advances concerning categories.
An epimorphism of groups is just a surjective homomorphism.
First, if G\xrightarrow {e} H is a surjective homomorphism, then given homomorphisms H\overset {f, g}{\rightrightarrows } K, we have that f = g because e is an epi in Set, so e is an epi.

Second, let G\xrightarrow {e} H be an epi in Grp. We wish to find a group K and two maps H\overset {f, g}{\rightrightarrows } K which agree on the image of e, hence are equal, in such a way that their equality allows us to conclude surjectivity of e. Let K be the symmetric group of the set of cosets H/e(G) with an adjoined point *.

Let H\xrightarrow {f} K be the map which sends h\in H to the associated permutation acting on kH by left translation and fixing *. Let \sigma \in K be the permutation which exchanges e(G) and *; let g be f composed with the inner automorphism associated to \sigma .

We finally claim that f(e(a)) = g(e(a)) for each a\in G. Indeed, since e(a)\in e(G), e(a) fixes e(G) and *, so is fixed under conjugation by \sigma . Now since e is an epi, f = g. Thus for each b\in H, f(b) = g(b), so that g(b) fixes f(H), i.e. bf(H) = f(H), so b\in f(H), as desired.
A cartesian closed category is a cartesian monoidal category whose monoidal structure is closed. In this case, we call the internal hom [x, y] an exponential object, and write it y^x.
The category of relations Rel has sets as objects and relations as morphisms. Composition is given by existence, i.e. a (SR) c if and only if there is some b such that aRb and bRc.

A closed monoidal category is a symmetric monoidal category C such that the bifunctor \otimes is closed. Explicitly, this means there is a bifunctor C^\text {op}\times C\xrightarrow {[-, -]} C, called the internal hom, together with a natural isormorphism C(x\otimes y, z)\cong C(x, [y, z]), called currying.
The counit of the adjunction (-\otimes y)\dashv [y, -] is called evaluation: it is a natural transformation [y, x]\otimes y\xrightarrow {\operatorname {ev}} x.

Applying the adjunction with x the monoidal unit I implies that maps y\to z are in natural bijection with maps I\to [y, z]. By the philosophy of generalized elements, this explains the name internal hom: its elements are maps.
A symmetric monoidal category is a braided monoidal category whose braiding \gamma satisfies \gamma _{x,y} = \gamma _{y,x}^{-1}.
A zero object is both initial and terminal.
In a category with a zero object 0, the canonical morphism x\to 0\to y induced by the universal properties of initial and terminal objects is called the zero morphism 0_{x,y}.
Sections are monomorphisms. Dually, retracts are epimorphisms.

fr:tree.fr:mainmatter: Let x\xrightarrow {s} y be a section with retract y\xrightarrow {r} s. Let z\overset {f, g}{\rightrightarrows } x be a parallel pair such that sf = sg. Then f = 1_xf = rsf = rsg = 1_xg = g, as desired.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: A monoidal category is cartesian if its monoidal product is the cartesian product (and so its monoidal unit is terminal); any category with finite products is monoidal in this way. Dually, it is cocartesian if it has finite coproducts, and bicartesian if it has both.
The endofunctor category C^C is (strict) monoidal with horizontal composition as the monoidal product and the identity functor as the monoidal unit.
